Yesterday, PG&E sent out by email?the attached?advice letter  filed last=20
Wednesday, 2057-E, which proposes to?implement revisions to all  electric=
=20
rate schedules and preliminary statements to change the Company=01,s rates =
 and=20
to bill customers based on PG&E=01,s flawed contention that the AB 1890  ra=
te=20
freeze has ended.? Based on accounting entries in its Transition Cost =20
Balancing Account (TCBA), PG&E says it completed recovery of its transition=
 =20
costs sometime before August 31, 2000, thus ending the rate freeze.?=20
?
This advice letter and the accompanying?tariff changes?are said  to be file=
d=20
in compliance with D.00-06-034, D.00-03-058, and D.99-10-057 in the =20
Post-Transition Electric Ratemaking (PTER) proceeding (A. 99-01-016).? =20
However, I believe it conflicts directly with the end of the rate freeze =
=20
mechanism which was specified in that proceeding.?=20
?
The August date for ending the rate freeze is based on the valuation of  PG=
&E=01,
s retained hydro assets of $2.8 billion, as included in the Company=01,s =
=20
Generation Asset Balancing Account ("GABA") filing effective June 23, 2000=
=20
as  filed in Advice Letters 2048-E and 2049-E, dated October 26, 2000.?=20
Based  on current market conditions PG&E believes the actual value will be =
=20
determined to be higher than $2.8 billion.? If this is the case, the rate =
=20
freeze will have ended earlier and the tariffs contained herein will be =20
revised.? If the actual value of such generation is lawfully determined to =
=20
be lower, PG&E says it will not seek recovery of any resulting =20
undercollected CTC.
?
This should be protested as it is an obvious effort to get out from under =
=20
their current purchased power undercollections at the expense of their =20
ratepayers, by making a spurious claim that the rate freeze has ended.? =20
There is no date specified for comments, but assuming the usual 20 days,=20
that  means protests are due on December 12.
